'''Annie Elizabeth Hoyle''' (1851–1931) was an artist from [[West Virginia]] who worked in the [[United States Forest Service]] from 1907 until 1930.<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|url=http://www.foresthistory.org/ASPNET/People/WO_Staffs/Hoyle.aspx|title=Annie E. Hoyle - USFS History - Forest History Society|website=www.foresthistory.org|access-date=2016-11-09}}</ref><ref name=":1">{{Cite web|url=http://www.uni-stuttgart.de/hi/gnt/dsi2/index.php?table_name=dsi&function=details&where_field=id&where_value=6420|title=DSI - Database of Scientific Illustrators|website=www.uni-stuttgart.de|access-date=2016-11-10}}</ref> Hoyle's drawings illustrated "The Pine Trees of the Rocky Mountain Region" authored by botanist [[George Bishop Sudworth|George Sudworth]].
== Early life and education == Annie Elizabeth Hoyle was born on a farm near [[Charles Town, West Virginia]].<ref name=":0" /><ref name=":1" /> Hoyle attended the Rouzee School of Fine Arts in [[Washington, D.C.|Washington, DC]] and then she relocated to New York City to study under George H. Story at the [[National Academy Museum and School|National Academy of Design]].<ref name=":0" /><ref name=":1" /> Hoyle studied plant morphology and botany at the [[National Museum of Natural History|US National Museum]] (predecessor to the Smithsonian) and at the [[Bureau of Plant Industry (United States)|Bureau of Plant Industry]] (United States Department of Agriculture.)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://wrenaissance-art.com/category/monday-morning-inspiration/|title=Monday Morning Inspiration {{!}} Wrenaissance Art|website=wrenaissance-art.com|access-date=2016-11-10}}</ref>
== Career == Hoyle started working for the Forest Service in 1908.<ref name=":0" /> She created over 160 drawings of range plants for the Division of Range Research during her twenty year career.<ref name=":0" /> Hoyle began working at the Forest Service after the age of 50 and stayed in the job until she retired at the age of 80.<ref name=":0" />
