==R==
{{glossary}}
{{term|1=Rake|content=[[Raking cornice|Rake]]  }}
{{defn|1=The diagonal outside facing edge of a gable, sometimes called a ''raking cornice'' or a ''sloping cornice''.  Rake is equivalent to slope which is the ratio of the rise to the run of the roof. }}

{{term|1= Rear vault }}
{{defn|1=[[Vault (architecture)|Vault]] of the internal hood of a doorway or window to which a splay has been given on the reveal, sometimes the vaulting surface is terminated by a small rib known as the scoinson rib, and a further development is given by angle shafts carrying this rib, known as scoinson shafts.<ref>{{cite EB1911|short=1 |wstitle=Rear Vault}}</ref> }}

{{term|1= Return }}
{{defn|1=Receding edge of a flat face. On a flat signboard, for example, the return is the edge which makes up the board's depth. }}

{{term|1= Revolving door }}
{{defn|1=An entrance door for excluding drafts from an interior of a building. A revolving door typically consists of three or four doors that hang on a center shaft and rotate around a vertical axis within a round enclosure. }}

{{term|1= Rib vault |content= [[Rib vault]] }}
{{defn|1=The intersection of two or three barrel vaults. }}

{{term|1= Ridge board |content= [[Ridge board]] }}
{{defn|1=A structural member that runs the length of the ridge (high point) on a sloped roof to which the upper ends of rafters are attached. }}

{{term|1= Roof comb |content= [[Roof comb]] }}
{{defn|1=The structure that tops a pyramid in monumental Mesoamerican architecture (also common as a decorative embellishment on the ridge of metal roofs of some domestic Gothic-style architecture in America in the 19th century). }}

{{term|1= Rotunda |content= [[Rotunda (architecture)|Rotunda]]}}
{{defn|1=A large and high circular hall or room in a building, usually but not always, surmounted by a dome. }}

{{glossary end}}

==S==
{{glossary}}

{{term|1= Sash|content= [[Sash window|Sash]] }}
{{defn|1=The horizontal and vertical frame that encloses the glazing of a window.  A sash may be fixed or operable and may be of several different types depending on operation (i.e. casement, single or double hung, awning, hopper or sliding). }}

{{term|1= Screens passage |content=[[Great hall|Screens passage]] }}
{{defn|1=The passage at one end of the [[Great hall]] of an English medieval house or castle, and separated from it by the spere. }}

{{term|1=Scroll |content=[[Scroll (art)|Scroll]] }}
{{defn|1=Ornamental element featuring a sequence of spiraled, circled or heart shaped motifs. There are, among others, flower scrolls, foliated scrolls, plants scrolls, vines scrolls. }}

{{term|1= Site-specific architecture |content= [[Site-specific architecture]] }}
{{defn|1= Architecture which is of its time and of its place. It is designed to respond to both its physical context, and the metaphysical context within which it has been conceived and executed}}

{{term|1= Sommer |content= Sommer or Summer {{anchor|sommer|summer}} }}
{{defn|1=Girder or main "summer beam" of a floor: if supported on two storey posts and open below, also called a "bress" or "breast-summer". Often found at the centerline of the house to support one end of a [[joist]], and to bear the weight of the structure above.<ref>{{cite EB1911|short=1 |wstitle=Sommer |volume=25 |page=393}}</ref> }}

{{term|1= Spandrel |content= [[Spandrel]] }}
{{defn|2=The space between two arches or between an arch and a rectangular enclosure|1=In a building facade, the space between the top of the window in one story and the sill of the window in the story above. }}

{{term|1= Spere }}
{{defn|1=The fixed structure between the great hall and the screens passage in an English medieval timber house.}}

{{term|1= Spire |content= [[Spire]] }}
{{defn|1=A tapering conical or pyramidal structure on the top of a building.}}

{{term|1= Springer |content= [[Springer (architecture)|Springer]] }}
{{defn|1=The lowest [[voussoir]] on each side of an arch. }}

{{term|1= Squinch |content= [[Squinch]] }}
{{defn|1=A piece of construction used for filling in the upper angles of a square room so as to form a proper base to receive an octagonal or spherical [[dome]]. }}

{{term|1= Squint |content= [[Hagioscope|Squint]] }}
{{defn|1=An opening, often arched, through an internal wall of a church providing an oblique view of the altar. }}

{{term|1= Stoop |content=[[Stoop (architecture)|Stoop]] }}
{{defn|1=A small [[staircase]] ending in a platform and leading to the entrance of an [[apartment building]] or other building. }}

{{term|1= Sunburst |content= [[Sunburst]] }}
{{defn|1=A design or figure commonly used in architectural ornaments and design patterns, including [[art nouveau]]. }}

{{term|1= Systyle }}
{{defn|1=in the [[classical order]]s, this describes columns rather thickly set, with an [[intercolumniation]] to which two diameters are assigned.<ref>{{cite EB1911|short=1 |wstitle=Systyle }}</ref> }}
{{glossary end}}

==T==
{{glossary}}
{{term|1= Timber framing |content= [[Timber framing]] }}
{{defn|1=Is the method of creating structures using heavy timbers jointed by pegged [[Mortise and tenon]] joints. }}

{{term|1= Trabeated arch |content= [[Trabeated arch]] }}
{{defn|1= An [[arch]] pointed at the top formed by [[voussoir]]s whose inside radius is greater than one-half the span of the arch.  }}

{{term|1= Tracery |content= [[Tracery]] }}
{{defn|1= The stonework elements that support the glass in a Gothic window.}}

{{term|1= Transom|content= [[Transom (architectural)]]}}
{{defn|1=Window or element, fixed or operable,  above a door but within its vertical frame. }}

{{term|1= Truss |content= [[Truss]] }}
{{defn|1=A structural component made of straight wood or metal members, usually in a triangular pattern, with "pinned" connections at the top and bottom chords and which is used to support structural loads, as those on a floor, roof or bridge. }}

{{term|1= Turret |content= [[Turret]] }} 
{{defn|1= A small tower that projects vertically from the wall of a building such as a medieval castle. }}

{{term|1= Tympanum |content= [[Tympanum (architecture)|Tympanum]] }}
{{defn|1=([[Greek (language)|Greek]] τύμπανον, from τύπτειν, to strike) the triangular space enclosed between the horizontal cornice of the entablature and the sloping cornice of the pediment. Though sometimes left plain, it is often decorated.}}
{{glossary end}}

==U==
{{glossary}}
{{term|1= Undercroft |content= [[Undercroft]] }}
{{defn|1=Traditionally, a cellar or storage room.  In modern usage, a ground-level area that is relatively open to the sides, but covered by the building above.  }}
{{glossary end}}

==V==
{{glossary}}
{{term|1= Ventilation shaft |content= [[Ventilation shaft]] }}
{{defn|1=A small, vertical space within a tall building which permits ventilation of the building. }}

{{term|1= Vierendeel truss |content= [[Truss#Vierendeel Truss|Vierendeel truss]] }}
{{defn|1=A rectilinear truss usually fabricated of steel or concrete with horizontal top and bottom chords and vertical web members (no diagonals) in which the loads imposed on it are transferred to the supports through bending forces resisted in its connections. }}

{{term|1= Volute |content= [[Volute]] }}
{{defn|1=A spiral, scroll-like ornament that forms the basis of the Ionic order. }}
{{glossary end}}

{{term|1= Voussoir|content= [[Voussoir]] }}
{{defn|1= A wedge-shaped or tapered stone between the springer and the keystone used to construct an arch. }}

==W==
