'''Physician, heal thyself''' ({{Lang-el|Ἰατρέ, θεράπευσον σεαυτόν}} — ''Iatre, therapeuson seauton''), sometimes quoted in the Latin form ''Medice, cura te ipsum'', is a [[proverb]] used in literary Classical texts from at least the 6th century BCE. The Greek dramatist [[Aeschylus]] refers to it in his ''[[Prometheus Bound]]'', where the chorus comments to the suffering Prometheus, "like an unskilled doctor, fallen ill, you lose heart and cannot discover by which remedies to cure your own disease."<ref>Herbert Weir Smyth, [http://www.theoi.com/Text/AeschylusPrometheus.html Theoi Classical Texts], lines 473–5</ref>

The moral of the proverb in general, containing within itself also a criticism of hypocrisy, is to attend to one's own defects before those in others.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia |editor=[[E. D. Hirsch, Jr.]] |editor2=Joseph F. Kett |editor3=[[James Trefil]] |title=Physician, heal thyself |encyclopedia=The New Dictionary of Cultural Literacy |publisher=[[Houghton Mifflin]] |location=[[Boston]] |year=2002 |isbn=0-618-22647-8 |oclc=50166721 |accessdate=2008-12-05 |url=http://www.bartleby.com/59/1/physicianhea.html |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080715040956/http://www.bartleby.com/59/1/physicianhea.html |archivedate=2008-07-15 |df= }}</ref> This meaning is underlined in the fable of [[The Frog and the Fox]] that was attributed to [[Aesop's Fables|Aesop]]. 

The same proverb also appeared in [[The Gospel According to Luke]], a Christian disciple who was a physician himself.<ref>{{Bibleverse|Colossians|4:14|KJV}}</ref> There he quoted Jesus as making a similar reference: "No doubt you will quote the proverb to me, 'Physician, heal yourself!' and say, 'We have heard of all your doings at [[Capernaum]]; do the same here in your own home town'."<ref>NEB, Luke 4:23</ref> At least one commentator has pointed out the echo of similar scepticism in the taunts that Jesus would ultimately hear while hanging on the cross: "He saved others; himself he cannot save. If he be the King of Israel, let him now come down from the cross, and we will believe him".<ref>Isaac Williams, ''The Gospel Narrative of Our Lord's Nativity Harmonized'', London 1844, [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=qnZjAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA384&lpg=PA384&dq=He+saved+others;+himself+he+cannot+save++%22Physician%22&source=bl&ots=5ubqFE34ss&sig=lrRQKdmgZuDnlpkKNrre2pLcp2E&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjQr_28p_neAhXNyqQKHfnsBpEQ6AEwBHoECAEQAQ#v=onepage&q=He%20saved%20others%3B%20himself%20he%20cannot%20save%20%20%22Physician%22&f=false p.384]</ref>

Similar proverbs with a medical theme appear in other Jewish literature.<ref>{{cite book |last=Nolland |first=J. |date=1979 |title=Classical and Rabbinic Parallels to "Physician, Heal Yourself" |url= |location= |publisher= |pages=193–209 |isbn= |author-link=}}</ref> "Physician, Physician, Heal thine own limp!", for example, can be found in [[Genesis Rabbah]] 23:4.<ref>Freedman, H., Simon, Maurice. ''Midrash Rabbah, Translated into English'', vol 1, p. 195</ref>

The shortened Latin form of the proverb, ''Cura te ipsum'', was made famous through the Latin translation of the Bible, the [[Vulgate]], and so gained currency across Europe.

