'''''The Swimming Hole''''' (also known as '''''Swimming''''' and '''''The Old Swimming Hole''''') is an 1884–85 painting by the American artist [[Thomas Eakins]] (1844–1916), [[List of works by Thomas Eakins|Goodrich catalog #190]], in the collection of the [[Amon Carter Museum of American Art]] in [[Fort Worth, Texas]]. Executed in [[oil on canvas]], it depicts six men [[skinny dipping|swimming naked]] in a lake, and is considered a masterpiece of American painting.{{sfn|Bolger|Cash|1996|p=vii}} According to art historian Doreen Bolger it is "perhaps Eakins' most accomplished rendition of the nude figure",{{sfn|Bolger|Barry|1994}} and has been called "the most finely designed of all his outdoor pictures".{{sfn|Goodrich|1982|p=239}} Since the [[Renaissance]], the human body has been considered both the [[Figure drawing|basis of artists' training]] and the most challenging subject to depict in art,{{sfn|Bolger|Cash|1996|p=1}} and the nude was the centerpiece of Eakins' teaching program at the [[Pennsylvania Academy of the Fine Arts]].{{sfn|Bolger|Barry|1994}} For Eakins, this picture was an opportunity to display his mastery of the human form.

In this work, Eakins took advantage of an exception to the generally prudish [[Victorian morality|Victorian]] attitude to [[nudity]]: swimming naked was widely accepted,{{sfn|Adams|2005|p=305}} and for males was seen as normal, even in public spaces. Eakins was the first American artist to portray one of the few occasions in 19th-century life when [[Depictions of nudity|nudity was on display]]. ''The Swimming Hole'' develops themes raised in his earlier work, in particular his treatment of [[buttocks]] and his ambiguous treatment of the human form; in some cases it is uncertain as to whether the forms portrayed are male or female. Such themes had earlier been examined in his ''[[The Gross Clinic]]'' (1875) and ''[[William Rush and His Model|William Rush]]'' (1877), and would continue to be explored in his paintings of boxers (''[[Taking the Count]]'', ''[[Salutat]]'', and ''[[Between Rounds]]'') and wrestlers (''[[Wrestlers (Eakins)|Wrestlers]]'').{{sfn|Adams|2005|p=306}}

Although the theme of male bathers was familiar in [[Western art history|Western art]], having been explored by artists from [[Michelangelo]] to [[Daumier]],{{sfn|Brown Price|1997|pp=56–63}} Eakins' treatment was novel in [[Visual arts of the United States|American art]] at the time. ''The Swimming Hole'' has been "widely cited as a prime example of homoeroticism in American art".{{sfn|Figliano|2005}} In 2008, the art critic Tom Lubbock described Eakins' work as:

{{quote|a classic of American painting. It shows a scene of healthy, manly, outdoor activity: a group of young fellows having stripped off for a dip. It is based on the swimming excursions that were enjoyed by the artist and his students. Eakins himself appears in the water at bottom right—in signature position, so to speak."{{sfn|Lubbock|2008}}}}

== Title and composition ==
[[Image:Dying gaul.jpg|thumb|The ''[[Dying Gaul]],'' [[Capitoline Museums]], Rome. This [[Hellenistic]] work of the late third century BC is believed to have been a source for the reclining figure on the far left of the painting.{{sfn|Sewell|1982|p=90}}]]
Eakins referred to the painting as ''Swimming'' in 1885, and as ''The Swimmers'' in 1886. The title ''The Swimming Hole''<!-- all in quotes - [[use–mention distinction]]--> dates from 1917 (the year after Eakins died), when the work was so described by the artist's widow, [[Susan Macdowell Eakins]]{{sfn|Bolger|Barry|1994}} Four years later, she titled the work ''The Old Swimming Hole'', in reference to the 1882 poem ''The Old Swimmin'-Hole''; by [[James Whitcomb Riley]].{{sfn|Adams|2005|pp=306–07}}{{sfn|Bolger|Cash|1996|pp=28–29}} The [[Amon Carter Museum]] has since returned to Eakins' original title, ''Swimming''.<!--so why is the article called what its called-->{{sfn|Amon Carter Museum|2007}}

The painting shows Eakins and five friends or students bathing at [[Dove Lake (Pennsylvania)|Dove Lake]], an artificial lake in [[Mill Creek (Montgomery County, Pennsylvania)|Mill Creek]] outside Philadelphia.{{sfn|Bolger|Barry|1994}} Each of the men is looking at the water, in the words of Martin A. Berger, "apparently lost in a contemplative moment".{{sfn|Berger|1997}} Eakins' precise rendering of the figures has enabled scholars to identify all those<!--not "men", since a dog is listed--> depicted in the work. They are (from left to right): [[Talcott Williams]] (1849–1928), Benjamin Fox (c.&nbsp;1865&nbsp;– c.&nbsp;1900), [[J. Laurie Wallace]] (1864–1953), Jesse Godley (1862–1889), Harry the dog (Eakins' [[Irish Setter]], c.&nbsp;1880–90), George Reynolds (c.&nbsp;1839–89), and Eakins himself.{{sfn|Berger|1997}} The rocky promontory on which several of the men rest is the foundation of the Mill Creek mill, which was razed in 1873. It is the only sign of civilization in the work—no shoes, clothes, or bath houses are visible.{{sfn|Bolger|Cash|1996|p=1}} The foliage in the background provides a dark background against which the swimmers' skin tones contrast.
[[File:Bazille, Frédéric ~ Summer Scene, 1869, Oil on canvas Fogg Art Museum, Cambridge, Massachusetts.jpg|thumb|left|[[Frédéric Bazille]]. ''[[Scène d'été]]'', 1869, [[oil on canvas]], {{frac|62|1|4}} × {{frac|62|1|2}}&nbsp;in (158 × 159&nbsp;cm), [[Fogg Art Museum]], [[Cambridge, Massachusetts]]. Eakins may have seen this painting while studying in Paris.{{sfn|Glueck|2004}}]] The composition is pyramidal. The figure reclining at left leads the viewer's eye to the seated figure, whose gesture in turn points to Godley at the apex of the compositional pyramid. The diving figure at right leads to the swimming form of Eakins, who painted himself into the scene and whose leftward movement directs attention back into the painting.{{sfn|Goodrich|1982|p=239}}{{sfn|Kirkpatrick|2006|p=285}} Eakins enforces this pyramidal structure by manipulating the [[Focus (optics)|focus]] of the painting: the center area containing the swimmers is extremely precise, while the outer areas are diffuse, with "virtually no moderating zones in between".{{sfn|Bolger|Cash|1996|pp=1–3}} The lighting within the picture is unnatural—too bright in some places, and too dark in others—although the effect, which tends to accentuate the body lines of the swimmers, is generally subtle.{{sfn|Bolger|Cash|1996|pp=1–3}}

The composition is notable for both its adherence to [[Academy#Academies of the arts|academic tradition]] (the mastery of the figure as an end in itself), and its uniqueness in transposing the male nude to an outdoor setting. The depiction of someone diving into water was very rare in the history of Western art.{{sfn|Bolger|Cash|1996|p=1}} The other figures are artfully arranged to imply a continuous narrative of movement, the poses progressing "from reclining to sitting to standing to diving"; at the same time, each figure is carefully positioned so that no genitalia are visible.{{sfn|Bolger|Cash|1996|p=1}} As in his previous works, Eakins chose to include a [[self-portrait]], here as the swimmer at bottom-right. Unlike his appearances in ''The Gross Clinic'' or ''[[Max Schmitt in a Single Scull]]'', here the artist's presence is more ambiguous—he may be seen as companion, teacher, or voyeur.{{sfn|Bolger|Cash|1996|p=66}} The ripple in the water next to Eakins, and the bubbles around the diver, are the only indications of movement in a painting where motion is otherwise arrested;{{sfn|Bolger|Cash|1996|p=66}} the water next to the red-headed figure in the lake is still enough to offer a clear reflection.{{sfn|Bolger|Cash|1996|p=25|ps=: Eakins himself said "There is so much beauty in reflections that it is generally worthwhile to try to get them right."}} This contrast underscores the tension in the picture between classical prototypes and scientific naturalism.{{sfn|Homer|1992|p=116}}

[[File:Thomas Eakins - Arcadia.jpg|thumb|[[Thomas Eakins]]. [[Arcadia (painting)|''Arcadia'']], 1883, {{frac|38|5|8}} × 45 in (98 × 114 cm), oil on canvas, [[The Metropolitan Museum of Art]]. Like ''The Swimming Hole'', this painting shows the influence of a classical conceit.{{sfn|Sewell|Foster|2001|p=113}}]]

The positioning of the bodies and their musculature refers to classical ideals of physical beauty and masculine camaraderie evocative of [[Greek art]].{{sfn|Getty Museum|2008}} The reclining figure is a paraphrase of the ''[[Dying Gaul]]'', and is juxtaposed with the far less formal self-depiction by the artist.{{sfn|Sewell|1982|p=90}} It is possible that Eakins was seeking to reconcile an ancient theme with a modern interpretation; the subject was contemporary, but the poses of some of the figures recall those of classical sculpture.{{sfn|Sewell|1982|pp=89–90}} One possible influence by a contemporary source was ''[[Scène d'été]]'', painted in 1869 by [[Frédéric Bazille]] (1841–70). It is not unlikely that Eakins saw the painting at the [[Salon (Paris)|Salon]] while studying in Paris, and would have been sympathetic to its depiction of male bathers in a modern setting.{{sfn|Glueck|2004}}

In Eakins' oeuvre, ''The Swimming Hole'' was immediately preceded by a number of similar works on the [[Arcadia (utopia)|Arcadian]] theme. These correspond to lectures he gave on [[Ancient Greek sculpture]] and were inspired by the Pennsylvania Academy's casts of [[Phidias]]' Pan-Athenaic procession from the [[Elgin Marbles|Parthenon marbles]].{{sfn|Sewell|Foster|2001|p=113}} A series of photographs, relief sculptures, and oil sketches culminated in the 1883 ''[[Arcadia (painting)|Arcadia]]'', a painting that also featured nude figures—posed for by a student, a nephew, and the artist's fiancée—in a pastoral landscape.{{sfn|Sewell|Foster|2001|p=113b|ps=: Eakins later gave the unfinished painting to [[William Merritt Chase]].}}

== Studies ==
Eakins made several on-site [[oil sketch]]es and photographic studies before painting ''The Swimming Hole''. It is unknown whether the photographs were taken before the oil sketches were produced or vice versa (or, indeed, whether they were created on the same day).

By the early 1880s, Eakins was using photography to explore sequential movement and as a reference for painting.{{sfn|Homer|1992|pp=116, 141–45}} Some time in 1883 or 1884, he photographed his students engaged in outdoor activities.{{sfn|Getty Museum|2008}} Four photographs of his students swimming naked in Dove Lake have survived, and bear a clear relationship to ''The Swimming Hole''. The swimmers are seen in the same spot and from the same vantage point, although their positions are entirely different from those in the painting. None of the photographs closely matches the poses depicted in the painting; this was unusual for Eakins, who typically adhered closely to his photographic studies. "The divergence between these sets of images may hint at lost or destroyed pictures, or it may tell us that the photographs came first, before Eakins' mental image had crystallized, and before the execution of his first oil sketch.{{sfn|Bolger|Cash|1996|pp=21–22}} The poses in the photographs are more spontaneous, while those of the painting are deliberately composed with a classical "severity".{{sfn|Goodrich|1982|p=239}} Although no photographic studies have survived that would suggest a more direct connection between the photographs and the painting, recent scholarship has proposed that marks incised onto the canvas and later covered by paint indicate that Eakins made use of light-projected photographs.{{sfn|Sewell|Foster|2001|pp=235–36}}
